  abstract = {Examined the dimensionality of Raven's Advanced Progressive Matrices (APM) using both exploratory and confirmatory factor analyses and compared findings with those of others by administering the full-length APM to 506 first-year college students (aged 17--30 yrs). Using the findings, the construction of a new short form of the test is described and its reliability tested in Study 2 with 94 students (aged 18--24 yrs). The effects of practice (Set I) on performance with the proposed short form was examined. Study 3, with 45 Ss (aged 18--27 yrs), tested the predictive utility of the new short form by examining its relation to a speed of information-processing measure known to be correlated with the full-length APM. Overall, it was concluded that, for most research purposes, when sampling from a first-year college sample, using only the first two items of Set I for instruction with either the proposed or W. Arthur and D. Day's (1994) short form of Set II will allow for substantial time savings without seriously compromising APM reliability or validity. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2019 APA, all rights reserved)},
